Identified issues¶

  • From previous experiment we can see why "recoverS" step (finding anchor words) fails: by scaling $C$ to have row sum $1$, we amplify the error of less frequent words; as a result, some less frequent words would appear at the extremal after scaling due to noise, so our "recoverS" step selects them instead.

  • Requiring input of "recoverS" to have rowsums to be $1$'s (as in A Practical Algorithm for Topic Modeling with Provable Guarantees) is not a necessary condition for the "recoverS" step (which is modified Gram-Schimdt with row pivoting) to work. In fact we can relax its assumptions:

Relax "sum-to-one" assumption¶

  • Suppose $E(\hat{X}) = X$ and $X = WH$ and $X$ satisifes anchor-word/separability assumption: rows of $H$ are scaled copies of some $K$ rows of $X$; the "sum-to-one" constraint requires $X$ to have rowsums to be all $1$'s. The resulting geometry is intuitive: the $K$ anchor words form the convex hull of all rows of $X$ (non-anchor rows can be expressed as convex combinations of anchor rows).

  • But we can relax "sum-to-one" constraint to be the following (let $S$ be the index set of anchor words):

    • At least one anchor word has rowsum $1$: $\text{max}_{j \in S} ||x^T_j||_p = 1$ for some $p \geq 1$
    • Non-anchor rows can be expressed as conic combinations of anchor rows, and the weights sum to no more than $1$: $\text{max}_{j} ||x^T_j||_p \leq 1$.

  • As a result, non-anchor rows live in the convex hull formed by anchor-rows and origin $\text{conv}(X_S, 0)$.

  • Therefore we can carefully choose the scaling of $X$ (or $C$ in our context below) so that the relaxed assumptions are satisfied, and noise are not amplified too much.

Experiments¶

  • Use the two datasets as in From previous experiment

  • I use the scaling strategies: "sum-to-one" ($\bar{C}_1$), "sum-to-one" scaling but denoising $C$ first ($\bar{C}_2$), no scaling ($\bar{C}_3$), scaling with cutoff ($\bar{C}_4$)

A very simple example¶

In [2]:
file = open(f'{datadir}/improve_C.pkl', 'rb')
out = pickle.load(file)
file.close()


X = out["X"]
Ftrue = out["Ftrue"]
Ltrue = out["Ltrue"]
Pi_true = out["Pi_true"]
Pi_eb = out["Pi"]
AB = out["AB"]
k = 3 ## forgot to store
n, p = X.shape

## truth
Ctrue = Pi_true.T @ Pi_true / n
Cbar0 = Ctrue / Ctrue.sum(axis = 1)[:, None]

Pi = X / X.sum(axis = 1)[:, None]
C = Pi.T @ Pi / n

## naive Cbar
Cbar1 = C / C.sum(axis = 1)[:, None] 

## apply EB shrinkage to estimate Pi, then construct CBar
Cbar2 = Pi_eb.T @ Pi_eb / n
Cbar2 /= Cbar2.sum(axis = 1)[:, None]

## Cbar without scaling C
Cbar3 = C / C.sum(axis = 1).max()

## C scaled with a cutoff
d = C.sum(axis = 1)
cutoff = np.quantile(d, [0.953])[0] ## need a more principled way to do this!!
d[d < cutoff] = cutoff
Cbar4 = C / d[:, None]

print(cutoff)
plt.hist(C.sum(axis = 1))
plt.axvline(x=cutoff, color = "red")
plt.show()

sidewalk¶

The diamond shape above implies very special structures; just to make sure it's not true for general matrix that has nonngetive factorization

In [20]:
F_ = np.random.uniform(size = (p, k))
L_ = np.random.uniform(size = (n, k))
Lam_ = L_ @ F_.T
Lam_ /= Lam_.sum(axis = 1)[:, None]
C_ = Lam_.T @ Lam_ / n
Cbar_ = C_ / C_.sum(axis = 1)[:, None]
Cbar_pj_ = pca_proj(Cbar_)

def vis_3d(coords):
	fig = plt.figure()
	ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
	
	x2 = coords[:, 0]
	y2 = coords[:, 1]
	z2 = coords[:, 2]
	ax.scatter(x2, y2, z2, s = 5, 
	        cmap='viridis', linewidth=0.5);

	# ax.set_ylim(y2.min(),y2.max())
	# ax.set_zlim(z2.min(),z2.max())


	plt.show()
